node.text:
Something that I’ve been preaching for a while now is allowing time in between draws to let the Joint breath. What I mean by this is giving the coal time to cool down in between hits as this will keep the smoke cooler offering more flavor while promoting better combustion and fewer burn issues. A few seconds in between is good, I personally like to do about 15-20 seconds and the flavor and burn is pleasant to say the least. For the purpose of this post, I tested for a whole minute to demonstrate how long a joint can sit for without burning out.
However, to allow something to breath for that long requires the joint itself to be rolled well enough to hold an ember. Often times we experience something that goes out frequently, requiring multiple re-lights. While there is nothing wrong with that, I personally do not like to re- light as each one affects the flavor a little more giving off a charred bitter taste at times.
Helpful advice to keep proper combustion is to make sure the flower it broken down according to the texture and consistency of the strain. Appropriately spreading the flower throughout the paper while avoiding gapping is crucial to the draw and airflow. Loose pockets and gapping are causes for burn outs and even burn issues like runners. The density at which you roll is also an important aspect of a proper burn. Roll it too tight and it’ll smolder but the draw will be lacking. Roll it too loose, and the joint will surely burn out. Finding the sweet spot coupled with the previously mentioned tips will help in ensuring things are smoking well.
It takes practice as well as patience, but once you dial in on it I promise you that it will change the experience for you and other that you smoke with and you will begin to appreciate the craft of rolling and the etiquette of smoking that much more. By  @roll_bmc

node.text: We started and developed @vibespapers from the ground up , we didn’t buy an existing paper company like some of the other big boys . I wanted to put the best hemp paper out & believe me , with all the politics and curve balls it took a while . Here we have our 100% organic non bleached ✨Vibe . This is thinner then our ultra thin and burns better than any other hemp paper that’s currently on the market . I had to do it right and I appreciate everyone that has been patient and waiting for this . I told you we would bring innovation to the game , and we did with the { Cubano } and the { Cali } . I know our haters are gonna be big mad and try and discredit this , all I ask is for them to please try .... organic hemp , natural acacia tree gum , no bleach , no chalk , non GMO , vegan 🌱 , thin and durable rolling paper baby ! I’ll take the Pepsi challenge any day ! Made for the smoker by the smoker ! I want to thank our partners in France 🇫🇷 and give a big shout out to our family in the Dominican Republic 🇩🇴! We are here to stay and couldn’t be prouder ! #vibespapers

How do you Tip? In-roll or external? What I mean by that is whether or not you roll with the tip in or if you add the tip in after rolling? Before I dive into how I personally implement the use of a tip, I first want to say that regardless of how you feel about using tips and filters, understand that there is a level of skill and knowledge required to roll with one and have things smoke well. It’s easier to roll without a tip than it is to properly roll with one.
While I’ve done and continue to do both methods, I’m personally more favorable to the in-roll method and I will explain why. Rolling with the tip in allows me to better gauge the length and density of the roll.
By using the size of the tip as a gauge and factoring in the texture of the flower, I can get a better feel for how things need to be spaced out and what intensity of pressure is needed to roll the body while matching the diameter of the tip. This allows for better consistency in airflow. When you roll without the tip and insert afterwards, you have to “eyeball” the density and diameter of the body to match the tip instead of using the tip to gauge the body. This can lead to issues such as a loose or unfitted tip that can lead to draw issues or worse, just simply falling off. You also run the risk of gapping where the tip meets the flower or the risk of rolling it too tight.
Another thing I do is roll with the tip extending past the paper itself, as shown in the video. This allows me to push the tip in after the roll to ensure a tight fit where the tip meets the flower. It also better prevents loose particles of flower from pulling into your mouth.
At the end of the day, the choice is yours on how you roll and smoke and practicing as many methods as possible will only make you more well rounded in this craft words from @roll_bmc

The beauty of rolling is that there are so many ways to do it. We all learn the foundations and then deviate from that to develop our own unique ways of technique, that’s what separates craft from party trick. Another thing that makes it a craft is being able to take inspiration from other places and incorporating it into something new. With traditional cigar rolling, size and shape come into play because each has an effect on the experience in flavor and volume of smoke; that is why you see all the different types of styles out there.
That is the inspiration behind the Cubano style shell. Taking inspiration from the Figurado shaped cigar style, the Pyramid this shape is known for its wide foot that tapers to a point at the head. It’s known to offer a complex smoking experience as the flavor and volume of smoke evolves as you progress through it. The wide foot, in this case around a 70 ring gauge(28mm) offers a higher ratio of flower to wrapper so the flavor is influenced more by the filler. It then gets passed through the tapered mouthpiece to produce a concentrated smoke stream that allows for a complex development of the flavor profile.
As you progress through the smoke, the body reduces in size to about a 50 ring gauge(15mm)which then changes the smoking experience as the flower becomes less influential and also where the body becomes more potent from the higher concentration of resins built up from distillation and condensation. Not only do you get an evolution of flavor, but also an increase in potency the further you smoke. That is the inspiration behind the Cubano, you know I had to put a little twist on it myself in the shape of a Cubano Donut!  Words from @roll_bmc
